To write a gRPC server request interceptor that logs each request including the body of the message in C#, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a new C# class that implements the `Grpc.Server.Interceptor` interface. This interface requires you to implement the `UnaryServerHandler` method.
2. In the `UnaryServerHandler` method, create a new instance of `ForwardingUnaryServerHandler` class, which will forward the request to the actual service implementation.
3. In the constructor of your interceptor class, store the service implementation and the `ForwardingUnaryServerHandler` instance.
4. Override the `UnaryServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse>` property to return a new instance of `LoggingUnaryServerHandler`, which will log the request body and call the forwarding handler.
5. Implement the `LoggingUnaryServerHandler` class that logs the request body using a `switch` statement, based on the type of the request message.

Here's the sample code:
```csharp
using Grpc.Core;
using Grpc.Core.Interceptors;

public class LoggingInterceptor : Interceptor
{
    private readonly UnaryServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse> _forwardingHandler;
    private readonly TServiceImpl _serviceImpl;

    public LoggingInterceptor(TServiceImpl serviceImpl)
    {
        _serviceImpl = serviceImpl;
        _forwardingHandler = new ForwardingUnaryServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse>(UnarySyncHandler);
    }

    public override UnaryServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse> UnaryServerHandler<TRequest, TResponse>()
    {
        return _forwardingHandler;
    }

    private TResponse UnarySyncHandler(TRequest request, ServerCallContext context, UnaryServerMethod<TRequest, TResponse> continuation)
    {
        LogRequestBody(request);
        return continuation(request, context);
    }

    private void LogRequestBody(TRequest request)
    {
        switch (request)
        {
            case ExampleRequest exampleRequest:
                // Log exampleRequest
                break;
            case AnotherExampleRequest anotherExampleRequest:
                // Log anotherExampleRequest
                break;
            // Add cases for other message types
            default:
                break;
        }
    }
}
```
Now, you can use the interceptor in your gRPC server by attaching it to the server service:
```csharp
public static void Main(string[] args)
{
    ServerServiceDefinition serviceDefinition = ServerServiceDefinition.CreateBuilder()
        .AddMethod(MyService.Descriptor.FindMethodByName("MyMethod"), MyMethodHandler)
        .Intercept(new LoggingInterceptor(new MyServiceImpl()))
        .Build();

    using var server = new Server
    {
        Services = { serviceDefinition },
        Ports = { new ServerPort("0.0.0.0", 50051, ServerCredentials.CreateInvokeCredentials()) }
    };

    server.Start();
    Console.WriteLine("gRPC server running, press enter to stop...");
    Console.ReadLine();
    server.Shutdown();
}
```
In this example, `MyServiceImpl` is the actual gRPC service implementation, and `MyMethodHandler` is the delegate for the gRPC method implementation. The interceptor is attached to the service definition using the `Intercept` method before creating the gRPC server.

