To log each gRPC request along with the message body in C#, you can create a custom interceptor class that inherits from the `Interceptor` class. In this custom class, you will override the `AsyncUnaryCall` method, which intercepts the incoming request, logs the necessary information, and then continues with the original RPC method call.

Below is an example of a basic gRPC server request interceptor in C# for logging requests with the message body:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Grpc.Core;
using Grpc.Core.Interceptors;
using Newtonsoft.Json;

public class LoggingInterceptor : Interceptor
{
    public override AsyncUnaryCall<TResponse> AsyncUnaryCall<TRequest, TResponse>(
        TRequest request,
        ClientInterceptorContext<TRequest, TResponse> context,
        AsyncUnaryCallContinuation<TRequest, TResponse> continuation)
    {
        LogRequest(context, request);

        var responseCall = continuation(request, context);

        return responseCall;
    }

    private void LogRequest<TRequest, TResponse>(ClientInterceptorContext<TRequest, TResponse> context, TRequest request)
        where TRequest : class
        where TResponse : class
    {
        var serviceName = context.Method.ServiceName;
        var methodName = context.Method.Name;
        var requestJson = JsonConvert.SerializeObject(request);

        // Replace Console.WriteLine with your preferred logging method
        Console.WriteLine($"Request to {serviceName}/{methodName} with body:");
        Console.WriteLine(requestJson);
    }
}
```

Now, you need to register the `LoggingInterceptor` in your gRPC service configuration. Below is an example of how to add the interceptor to a gRPC server:

```csharp
using System;
using Grpc.Core;

public class Program
{
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        const int Port = 50051;
        var interceptor = new LoggingInterceptor();
        var server = new Server
        {
            Services = 
            {
                // Add your gRPC service(s) here using `Intercept()`
                YourGrpcService.BindService(new YourGrpcServiceImpl()).Intercept(interceptor)
            },
            Ports = { new ServerPort("localhost", Port, ServerCredentials.Insecure) }
        };

        server.Start();

        Console.WriteLine($"Server listening on port {Port}");
        Console.ReadKey();

        server.ShutdownAsync().Wait();
    }
}
```

Remember to replace `YourGrpcService` and `YourGrpcServiceImpl` with the appropriate gRPC service and service implementation names in your project. This example will log each incoming request with its message body for all the methods in `YourGrpcService`.

