Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) is a powerful technique to find and analyze patterns in different data series, such as sounds, images, and even stock prices. Before diving into the C# code, let's discuss the basic idea behind FFT and how it can help with pattern matching.

FFT converts a signal from the time domain to the frequency domain, highlighting the signal's dominant frequencies. By comparing the frequencies of two signals, you can determine if they share any common patterns.

For pattern matching with FFT, we'll use Cross-Correlation, which measures the similarity between two signals. Higher values indicate higher similarity.

Here's an example of C# code to perform pattern matching using FFT with the help of the MathNet.Numerics library:

1. Install MathNet.Numerics:
To use FFT in C#, first, you need to install the MathNet.Numerics library through NuGet package manager:

```shell
Install-Package MathNet.Numerics
```

2. C# Code:
Now, use the following code to perform FFT-based pattern matching in C#:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Linq;
using MathNet.Numerics;
using MathNet.Numerics.IntegralTransforms;

public class FFTPatternMatching
{
    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // Input data (time-series)
        double[] signal = { ... }; // Your main signal/source data
        double[] pattern = { ... }; // Your pattern/search data

        // Perform FFT on both data series
        Complex[] signalFFT = signal.Select(x => new Complex(x, 0)).ToArray();
        Complex[] patternFFT = pattern.Select(x => new Complex(x, 0)).ToArray();

        Fourier.Forward(signalFFT);
        Fourier.Forward(patternFFT);

        // Compute cross-correlation
        Complex[] crossCorrelation = CrossCorrelation(signalFFT, patternFFT);

        // Perform inverse FFT on cross-correlation
        Fourier.Inverse(crossCorrelation);

        // Find maximum value and its index in crossCorrelation array
        int maxIndex = 0;
        double maxValue = crossCorrelation[0].Magnitude;

        for (int i = 1; i < crossCorrelation.Length; i++)
        {
            if (crossCorrelation[i].Magnitude > maxValue)
            {
                maxValue = crossCorrelation[i].Magnitude;
                maxIndex = i;
            }
        }

        Console.WriteLine($"Pattern occurs at index: {maxIndex}");
    }

    private static Complex[] CrossCorrelation(Complex[] a, Complex[] b)
    {
        // Compute the conjugate of b
        Complex[] conjugateB = b.Select(x => x.Conjugate()).ToArray();

        // Perform element-wise multiplication of a and conjugateB
        Complex[] product = new Complex[a.Length];
        for (int i = 0; i < a.Length; i++)
        {
            product[i] = a[i] * conjugateB[i];
        }

        return product;
    }
}
```

This code will find the starting index of the pattern inside the signal. Note that the input signal and pattern should have the same size. You can use zero-padding to adjust their sizes accordingly.

