The `ListProcessor` class takes an input list of strings and returns a new list with duplicates removed while maintaining the original order of elements. The `processList` method checks if the input list is empty or contains only one element, and if so, it returns an empty list. If the input list is valid, the `processList` method loops through the list and checks if each element has been seen before. If an element has not been seen before, it is added to a set called `seen` and also to a new list called `filteredList`. Finally, the `filteredList` is returned as the output list.

The `main` method creates an instance of `ListProcessor` and passes a sample input list to the `processList` method. If an error occurs during the execution of the `processList` method, it is caught and printed as an error message.

Note: We use a `LinkedHashSet` instead of a `HashSet` to maintain the order of the elements in the `seen` set, since a `HashSet` does not maintain the order of its elements.

